
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `mandb` database-haye `man` page ra update mikonad. Yani, index-e `man` page-ha ra tazeh mikonad ta vaghti ke shoma `man [dastoor]` ra mizani, `man` betoone page-e mored nazar ro peyda kone.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `mandb -c`  --> 🔄 Database-haye ghabli ro pak mikone va az aval misaze. Age moshkeli darid, az in estefade konid.
    🔹 `mandb -q`  --> 🤫 Hich peyghami namayesh nade, yani "quiet" bashe.
    🔹 `mandb -d`  --> 🔍 Faghat debug kone va database ro update nakone.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ sudo mandb

    🔹 Database-e `man` page-ha ro update mikone ba dastresi admin.

    $ sudo mandb -c

    🔹 Database ro az aval misaze, baraye halle moshkelat.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ mandb
 
    🔹  Agar page man ha dorost kar nemikonad, `mandb` database ha ra update mikonad va problem ra fix mikonad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `mandb` command updates the `man` page databases. This means it refreshes the index of `man` pages so that when you type `man [command]`, `man` can find the appropriate page.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `mandb -c`  --> 🔄 Clears existing databases and recreates them from scratch. Use this if you encounter issues.
    🔹 `mandb -q`  --> 🤫 Doesn't display any messages; operates in "quiet" mode.
    🔹 `mandb -d`  --> 🔍 Only debugs and doesn't update the database.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ sudo mandb

    🔹 Updates the `man` page databases with administrator privileges.

    $ sudo mandb -c

    🔹 Rebuilds the databases from scratch, useful for resolving errors.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ mandb

    🔹 If the man pages are not working correctly, `mandb` updates the databases and fixes the problem.
